The optical properties of products were studied. The PL spectrum of blue emission (Em) CDs and the emission peak was at 450 nm, as shown in Fig. 3
                        (a). The color of CDs was blue in ultraviolet light and yellow in sunlight (inset of Fig. 3(a)). It could be found that the peak position of CDs slowly occurred a red shift with the increase of excitation wavelength, indicated that CDs had PL dependence (Fig. 3(b)). From Fig. 3(c), the strong emission peak of the obtained CuNCs at 647 nm. Meanwhile, there was a main excitation peak at 345 nm in excitation spectrum, which is also consistent with 350 nm in the UV–vis spectra (Fig. 3(c)). The color of CuNCs was red in ultraviolet light and milky white in sunlight (inset of Fig. 3(c)). In a similar way, the peak position of CuNCs basically did not change when the excitation wavelength gradually increased, indicated that CuNCs was not PL dependence (Fig. 3(d)). When the excitation wavelengths were 345 and 360 nm, the optimal emission wavelengths of CuNCs and CDs were 647 and 450 nm, respectively (Fig. 4
                        ). When CDs-CuNCs nano-composites were excited at 345 nm, there were emission peaks were obtained at 647 and 430 nm. This also further confirmed the successful synthesis of dual-emission CDs-CuNCs nano-composites.
